[
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Measures.20on.20R.5En/near/462993481\">this topic</a>, I've asked how do we formalise measures on R^n. Here's a more specific question which I'm trying to solve.</p>\n<p>I am trying to formalise Gaussian measures, and decided to start from the case of R^n. A Borel measure gamma on R^n is said to be Gaussian if for every linear functional R^n -&gt; R the induced measure gamma o l^{-1} is a Gaussian measure on R. Here's my attempt at formalising this definition:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">isGaussianReal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ProbabilityMeasure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">isGaussianFinDim</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ProbabilityMeasure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">BorelSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)]:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"n\">L</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">AEMeasurable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"o\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">isGaussianReal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ProbabilityMeasure</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">γ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>However, assuming <code>h : AEMeasurable l γ</code> seems unnecessary, which brings me to the following two quesions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Where did I specify that <code>n → ℝ</code> is endowed with the Borel sigma-algebra? Is it somehow inferred? If yes, how should I find the definition?</li>\n<li>Is there a way to avoid this assumption? It's not really needed.</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 463047015,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723927846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>P.S. If I remove <code>[BorelSpace n → ℝ]</code>, nothing changes, this was just my attempt to put this assumption somewhere</p>",
        "id": 463049244,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723928767
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, <code>n \\to \\R</code> is automatically endowed with borel sigma algebra (see <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Real.borelSpace#doc\">docs#Real.borelSpace</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Pi.borelSpace#doc\">docs#Pi.borelSpace</a>)</p>",
        "id": 463049854,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1723929349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And you can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Continuous.aemeasurable#doc\">docs#Continuous.aemeasurable</a></p>",
        "id": 463049933,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1723929419
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you want to know how an instance is synthesized, you can do</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Finite</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">synth</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">BorelSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 463050140,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1723929631
    }
]